gland":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Bromham, Sussex, England":"Sussex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Peverel","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Peverall  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Peverall","meanings":["Norman, English: relationship name from Old French  <i>Peurel</i> (Latin  <i>Piperellus</i>), a diminutive of Old French  <i>pevre</i> ‘pepper’ (Anglo-Norman French  <i>peivere</i>, Latin  <i>piper</i>), originally perhaps used as a nickname on the Continent but used as a personal name in Anglo-Norman England."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Peverel was born in 1159, in Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Hamon Peverel, was 44 and his mother, Peverel, was 45. He had at least 2 daughters with Adelocia Towmay. He died in 1210, in Suffolk, England, at the age of 51, and was buried in Suffolk, England."},"et":{"1159–1210":"1159–1210","1163–Female":"1163–Surnud","1195–1267":"1195–1267","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","1115–1159":"1115–1159","1115–Female":"1115–Surnud","Abt 1195":"umbes 1195","1159":"1159","1115":"1115","1267":"1267","1210":"1210","1163":"1163","1195":"1195","Bourne Hall, Brunne, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England","Ely, Cambridgeshire, England":"Ely, Cambridgeshire, England","Bromham, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Bromham, Sussex, England":"Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1159–1210":"1159–1210","1163–Female":"1163–Kuollut","1195–1267":"1195–1267","1210–Female":"1210–Kuollut","1115–1159":"1115–1159","1115–Female":"1115–Kuollut","Abt 1195":"noin 1195","1159":"1159","1115":"1115","1267":"1267","1210":"1210","1163":"1163","1195":"1195","Bourne Hall, Brunne, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England","Ely, Cambridgeshire, England":"Ely, Cambridgeshire, England","Bromham, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Bromham, Sussex, England":"Sussex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1159–1210":"1159–1210","1163–Female":"1163–Décédée","1195–1267":"1195–1267","1210–Female":"1210–Décédée","1115–1159":"1115–1159","1115–Female":"1115–Décédée","Abt 1195":"environ 1195","1159":"1159","1115":"1115","1267":"1267","1210":"1210","1163":"1163","1195":"1195","Bourne Ha